Day 2 — Linux Users, Groups, Permissions & Sudo

Portfolio Artifact Name: Phase1_Day2_UserMgmt

1️⃣ Lab Metadata
Lab Name: Day 2 — Linux Users, Groups, Permissions & Sudo
Phase: Phase 1 – Core Systems
Objective: Implement user and group management, configure file permissions, and enable sudo privileges for secure operations.
Disciplines Covered: Linux Systems, Security, DevOps Foundation
Roles Enabled: Linux SysAdmin, Junior DevOps Engineer, DevOps Engineer
Estimated Duration: 2–3 hours
Dependencies: Day 1 – Linux Core Setup, Static IP
Lab Version: 1.0
Date: 2026-02-07
2️⃣ Lab Overview / Consulting Context

Proper user and permission management is critical for secure and compliant operations. Misconfigured users, groups, or sudo privileges can lead to data breaches or operational failures. This lab builds the foundation for enterprise-grade Linux access control, directly relevant to AWS IAM analogs for SAA and hybrid multi-node setups for SAP.

3️⃣ Prerequisites

Day 1 completed (VM up, static IP configured, SSH working)

Root or sudo access to VM

Terminal / SSH client

4️⃣ Step-by-Step Lab Execution (With Objectives)
Step 1 — Add Users

Objective: Create users for operational and administrative purposes.

# Add a regular user
sudo adduser devops1
# Add a system/admin user
sudo adduser fsieadmin

Explanation: Separate accounts for security and audit; aligns with least privilege principle.

Step 2 — Add Groups

Objective: Group users to simplify permissions management.

# Create groups
sudo groupadd devops
sudo groupadd admins

# Add users to groups
sudo usermod -aG devops devops1
sudo usermod -aG admins fsieadmin

Explanation: Groups allow centralized permission control; mirrors AWS IAM groups.

Step 3 — Configure File & Directory Permissions

Objective: Control access to critical directories and files.

# Create project directory
sudo mkdir /srv/fsie-project
sudo chown fsieadmin:admins /srv/fsie-project
sudo chmod 770 /srv/fsie-project

Explanation: Only admins and authorized users can access; enforces principle of least privilege.

Step 4 — Sudo Privileges

Objective: Grant controlled administrative access to users.

# Edit sudoers safely
sudo visudo

# Add user
fsieadmin ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL
devops1 ALL=(ALL) ALL

Explanation: fsieadmin can run any command without password (for automation), devops1 requires password — mimics controlled escalation.

Step 5 — Test Permissions

Objective: Validate access rights.

# Switch user and test
su - devops1
ls -l /srv/fsie-project   # Should be readable/writeable only for allowed users

su - fsieadmin
touch /srv/fsie-project/test.txt  # Should succeed
Step 6 — Document Users & Permissions

Objective: Maintain enterprise-grade audit trail.

# List users
cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd

# List groups
cut -d: -f1 /etc/group

# List sudoers
sudo cat /etc/sudoers

Artifact: Users_Groups_Permissions.md — documents setup for portfolio

5️⃣ Automation Scripts / Config Files

UserMgmt_Setup.sh

#!/bin/bash
# Add users
sudo adduser devops1 --gecos "" --disabled-password
sudo adduser fsieadmin --gecos "" --disabled-password

# Add groups
sudo groupadd devops
sudo groupadd admins

# Assign users to groups
sudo usermod -aG devops devops1
sudo usermod -aG admins fsieadmin

# Directory setup
sudo mkdir -p /srv/fsie-project
sudo chown fsieadmin:admins /srv/fsie-project
sudo chmod 770 /srv/fsie-project

# Sudoers setup
echo "fsieadmin ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL" | sudo tee -a /etc/sudoers
echo "devops1 ALL=(ALL) ALL" | sudo tee -a /etc/sudoers

Users_Groups_Permissions.md — documents all users, groups, directories, permissions, sudo access

6️⃣ Failure Injection & Observability

Scenario 1: devops1 cannot access restricted directory → fix ownership/permissions
Scenario 2: fsieadmin sudo misconfigured → simulate automation failure
Scenario 3: Group membership missing → simulate audit failure

Artifacts:

FailureInjection_Day2.txt → steps & observations

FailureInjection_Day2.png → screenshots/logs

